  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "Bearish daily trend with 10 consecutive down candles; analyst examines how previous day high/low sweeps created broadening formations on the daily chart, which then served as reversal POIs and expansion targets on lower time frames.",
  "key_observation": "When both previous day high and low are taken (swept), it forms a broadening formation on the daily chart—visually an outside bar—which can be extended to project targets and identify reversal zones.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: The analyst identified the initial range high and low on the hourly chart and marked them as a point of interest for price to retrace into.",
    "Step 2: He switched to the daily chart and noted that the previous day’s high and low were both taken, forming a broadening formation (i.e., an outside bar on the daily timeframe).",
    "Step 3: He extended the broadening formation lines outward to use them as future targets and points of interest for reversals.",
    "Step 4: He connected this to the daily profile concept: when London sweeps Asia high/low, New York uses London’s high/low as POIs—and if those also form broadening structures, they reinforce reversal zones.",
    "Step 5: On the 15-minute chart, he showed how the extended broadening lines framed actual reversal points after NY session expansion."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Broadening formations on the daily chart—created by outside bars that sweep both prior day extremes—are high-probability POIs. Extending their boundaries provides clean targets and reversal zones aligned with session-based daily profiles.",
